[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 14.7: OR Case Sequencing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium-Complex · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$200-800/month (solver compute)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It's 5:45 AM at a 20-OR hospital. The charge nurse is staring at today's surgical schedule: 47 cases across 12 rooms. The orthopedic surgeon wants his total knee first because "the patient needs to be in recovery by noon." The cardiac team needs Room 4 because it's the only one with the perfusion setup. Two cases need the same robotic system. The anesthesiologist covering rooms 6 through 9 has a hard stop at 3 PM. And someone just called in a semi-urgent appendectomy that needs to fit somewhere before lunch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is OR case sequencing: deciding not just which cases happen today, but in what order, in which rooms, and at what times. It's a puzzle that perioperative teams solve manually every single day, usually starting at 4 AM, usually with a whiteboard and a lot of phone calls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cost of getting it wrong is real. A poorly sequenced day means turnover gaps where rooms sit empty between cases (each minute of unused OR time costs $30-60 depending on the facility). It means the 3 PM case that was supposed to be a 90-minute procedure starts at 4:15 because everything upstream ran long, and now you're paying overtime for the entire surgical team. It means the equipment conflict nobody caught until the patient was already prepped.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most hospitals run their ORs at 60-70% utilization. The theoretical ceiling with perfect sequencing is closer to 80-85% (you can't hit 100% because of mandatory turnover time and inherent duration uncertainty). That gap between actual and achievable utilization represents millions in lost revenue annually for a mid-size hospital. Not because the cases aren't there, but because the sequence is suboptimal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The manual approach works. It has worked for decades. But it works the way a human playing chess works: by pattern recognition and heuristics, not by evaluating all possible arrangements. A 12-room, 47-case day has a combinatorial space that no human can fully explore. Optimization can.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Combinatorial Optimization for Scheduling
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Is Combinatorial Optimization?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its core, OR case sequencing is a constrained scheduling problem. You have a set of jobs (surgical cases), a set of machines (operating rooms), and a set of constraints (equipment availability, staff schedules, surgeon preferences, patient medical requirements). You want to find an assignment and ordering that optimizes some objective (minimize total idle time, minimize overtime, maximize throughput, or some weighted combination).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This falls squarely into the domain of combinatorial optimization, specifically a variant of the job-shop scheduling problem. The "combinatorial" part means the number of possible solutions grows factorially with the number of cases. Ten cases in one room have 10! = 3.6 million possible orderings. Forty-seven cases across twelve rooms? The solution space is astronomically large.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### How Solvers Work
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You don't enumerate all possibilities. Instead, you formulate the problem mathematically and hand it to a solver, a piece of software designed to find optimal (or near-optimal) solutions to these kinds of problems efficiently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m There are two main families of solvers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mixed-Integer Programming (MIP) solvers.** These formulate the problem as a set of linear equations with some variables constrained to be integers (typically 0 or 1, representing "yes this case goes in this slot" or "no it doesn't"). The solver uses branch-and-bound algorithms to systematically explore the solution space, pruning branches that can't possibly beat the best solution found so far. Commercial MIP solvers (Gurobi, CPLEX) are remarkably good at this. They can prove optimality: "this is the best possible solution given your constraints." Open-source options (COIN-OR CBC, HiGHS, SCIP) are capable but slower on large instances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Constraint Programming (CP) solvers.** These are particularly well-suited to scheduling problems because they natively understand concepts like "this task must come before that task" and "these two tasks can't overlap on the same resource." CP solvers use propagation and search: they infer consequences of partial assignments (if case A is in room 3 at 8 AM, then case B can't be in room 3 until at least 10:30 AM) and use those inferences to prune the search space. Google's OR-Tools CP-SAT solver is excellent and free.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Metaheuristics.** For very large instances or when you need a good solution fast (real-time replanning), metaheuristics like simulated annealing, genetic algorithms, or large neighborhood search can find high-quality solutions without guaranteeing optimality. They're the "good enough in 5 seconds" option when the MIP solver would take 20 minutes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Constraint Formulation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The art of OR case sequencing isn't choosing a solver. It's formulating the constraints correctly. Here's what a typical formulation includes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decision variables:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Which room is each case assigned to?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - What position in the sequence does each case occupy within its room?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - What is the start time of each case?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hard constraints (must be satisfied):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - No two cases overlap in the same room
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Turnover time between consecutive cases in the same room (typically 20-45 minutes depending on case type)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Equipment availability: if two cases need the same robot, they can't overlap
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Staff availability windows: the anesthesiologist covering rooms 6-9 is only available until 3 PM
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Room capability: cardiac cases can only go in rooms with bypass capability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient medical constraints: "this patient must be first case of the day" (NPO requirements, pediatric cases, immunocompromised patients needing sterile-first rooms)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Soft constraints (preferences, penalized if violated):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Surgeon sequence preferences ("I want my complex case first while I'm fresh")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Minimize total overtime across all rooms
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Minimize maximum overtime in any single room (fairness)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Group similar cases to reduce turnover time (two knee replacements back-to-back need less room reconfiguration than a knee followed by a craniotomy)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Minimize patient wait time from scheduled arrival to OR entry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Objective function:** Typically a weighted sum of soft constraint violations plus utilization metrics. The weights encode institutional priorities: "we care more about avoiding overtime than about surgeon preferences" or vice versa.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Duration Uncertainty: The Hard Part
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's where OR case sequencing gets genuinely difficult. Case durations are uncertain. A "90-minute" total knee replacement might take 70 minutes or 130 minutes depending on patient anatomy, complications, and how the surgeon's morning is going. This uncertainty propagates through the sequence: if case 1 runs 30 minutes long, every subsequent case in that room shifts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m There are three approaches to handling this:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deterministic with buffers.** Use expected durations plus a safety margin. Simple, but either too conservative (wasted time) or too aggressive (frequent overruns). Most manual scheduling works this way.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stochastic optimization.** Model durations as probability distributions (typically lognormal for surgical cases) and optimize the expected value of the objective. More sophisticated, but computationally expensive and requires good historical data to fit the distributions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Robust optimization.** Find a schedule that performs well across a range of duration scenarios, not just the expected case. This is the "minimax regret" approach: minimize the worst-case outcome. Conservative but resilient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For most implementations, deterministic with intelligent buffers (based on historical variance per procedure type and surgeon) is the pragmatic starting point. Graduate to stochastic methods once you have solid duration prediction models (see Recipe 7.7: Length of Stay Prediction for related techniques).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Batch vs. Real-Time Optimization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Two distinct operational modes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Batch (overnight planning).** Run the full optimization the evening before or early morning. Takes the confirmed case list, applies all constraints, and produces the day's schedule. Can afford to run for minutes because there's no one waiting. This is where MIP solvers shine: give them 5-10 minutes and they'll find a provably optimal or near-optimal solution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time (intraday replanning).** A case cancels at 9 AM. An emergency add-on arrives at 11 AM. A case runs 45 minutes over. The morning's optimal schedule is now suboptimal or infeasible. You need a new plan in seconds, not minutes. This is where metaheuristics or warm-started CP solvers earn their keep: take the current state, fix what's already happened, and re-optimize the remainder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most production systems need both: batch for the initial plan, real-time for adjustments throughout the day.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Case Data] → [Constraint Builder] → [Solver Engine] → [Schedule Output]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m      ↑                                                        ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Duration Models] ← [Historical Data]              [Visualization / Alerts]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m      ↑                                                        ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Real-time Events] → [Replan Trigger] → [Warm-start Solver] → [Updated Schedule]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data ingestion layer.** Pulls the case list from the surgical scheduling system (typically via HL7 or FHIR integration with the EHR). Enriches each case with: estimated duration (from historical models), equipment requirements (from preference cards), staff assignments, room constraints, and patient-specific requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Constraint builder.** Translates business rules into mathematical constraints. This is the layer that encodes "Dr. Smith only operates in rooms 1-4" and "the da Vinci robot needs 30 minutes of setup between cases" into the solver's language. Separating constraint definition from the solver itself is critical: business rules change frequently, and you don't want to rewrite solver code every time a new surgeon joins.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Solver engine.** The optimization core. Accepts the constraint model and produces an optimal or near-optimal schedule. Should support both batch mode (full optimization from scratch) and warm-start mode (fix completed cases, re-optimize the rest).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Schedule output and visualization.** The optimized schedule needs to be consumable by humans (perioperative coordinators, charge nurses, surgeons) and by systems (EHR, patient tracking boards, equipment management). A Gantt-style visualization showing rooms on the Y-axis and time on the X-axis is the standard display.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Replan trigger.** Monitors real-time events (case completions, cancellations, add-ons, duration overruns) and decides when to trigger re-optimization. Not every event needs a full replan. A case finishing 5 minutes early doesn't warrant disruption. A case finishing 45 minutes late, or a cancellation that frees a room, does.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for the constraint builder and orchestration.** The constraint-building step is stateless computation: take case data, apply rules, produce a model. Lambda handles this cleanly. The orchestration layer (triggering batch runs, handling replan events) is also a natural Lambda workload.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon ECS (Fargate) for the solver engine.** Optimization solvers are CPU-intensive and memory-hungry. A 50-case problem might need 4-8 GB of RAM and several minutes of sustained CPU. Lambda's 15-minute timeout and 10 GB memory limit technically work for batch mode, but Fargate gives you more control over compute resources, no cold-start penalty for warm-start replanning, and the ability to run commercial solvers that require persistent licensing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for case data and schedule state.** The current schedule, case metadata, and constraint parameters need low-latency reads (for the real-time replan path) and consistent writes (to prevent conflicting schedule updates). DynamoDB's single-digit-millisecond reads and conditional writes fit perfectly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for real-time event routing.** Case completions, cancellations, and add-ons arrive as events from the EHR integration. EventBridge routes these to the replan trigger logic, which decides whether to invoke re-optimization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for historical data and model artifacts.** Duration prediction models, historical case logs, and optimization run artifacts (for audit and analysis) live in S3.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SQS for the replan queue.** When multiple events arrive in quick succession (common during the morning rush), SQS buffers replan requests and ensures they're processed sequentially. You don't want three concurrent replans fighting over the same schedule state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[EHR / Surgical Scheduling] -->|HL7/FHIR| B[EventBridge\nCase Events]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|New/Modified Cases| C[Lambda\nConstraint Builder]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Cancellation/Completion| D[Lambda\nReplan Trigger]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C --> E[DynamoDB\nCase Data & Constraints]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E --> F[ECS Fargate\nSolver Engine]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F --> G[DynamoDB\nOptimized Schedule]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Replan Needed?| H[SQS\nReplan Queue]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I[S3\nHistorical Data] --> J[Lambda\nDuration Predictor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G --> K[API Gateway\nSchedule API]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K --> L[OR Dashboard\nGantt View]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Lambda, ECS (Fargate), DynamoDB, EventBridge, SQS, S3, API Gateway |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `ecs:RunTask`, `dynamodb:GetItem/PutItem/Query`, `s3:GetObject/PutObject`, `sqs:SendMessage/ReceiveMessage`, `events:PutEvents` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required: case data includes patient identifiers and procedure details (PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; all transit over TLS; ECS task roles with least-privilege |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Fargate tasks in private subnets with VPC endpoints for DynamoDB, S3, SQS, CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls; schedule changes auditable |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic surgical case lists. Use realistic procedure mixes and durations from published OR benchmarking data. Never use real patient data in dev. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Fargate solver: ~$0.05-0.20 per optimization run (2-4 vCPU, 8 GB, 1-10 min). Lambda + DynamoDB: negligible. Monthly: $200-800 depending on replan frequency. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Constraint building, duration prediction, replan trigger logic |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon ECS (Fargate)** | Runs the optimization solver (CP-SAT, HiGHS, or commercial) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores case data, constraints, and current optimized schedule |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Routes real-time surgical events (completions, cancellations, add-ons) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SQS** | Buffers replan requests to prevent concurrent optimization conflicts |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Historical case data, duration models, optimization audit logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | Exposes schedule API for dashboard and EHR integration |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for PHI at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Ingest and enrich case data.** When the daily case list is finalized (typically by 4-5 PM the day before), the system pulls each case's details and enriches them with predicted duration, equipment needs, and constraint metadata. The duration prediction uses historical data for the specific procedure-surgeon combination. This enrichment step is what transforms a simple case list into an optimization-ready dataset. Skip it and the solver has no basis for intelligent sequencing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION enrich_case_list(raw_cases):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull the confirmed case list and add optimization-relevant metadata.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     enriched = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each case in raw_cases:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Predict duration using historical procedure-surgeon data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The prediction includes mean and standard deviation for buffer calculation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         duration_estimate = predict_duration(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure_code = case.cpt_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surgeon_id     = case.surgeon_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_asa    = case.asa_class    // sicker patients take longer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Look up equipment requirements from the surgeon's preference card.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         equipment_needs = get_preference_card(case.surgeon_id, case.cpt_code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Build the enriched case record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         enriched_case = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             case_id:          case.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             procedure:        case.cpt_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surgeon_id:       case.surgeon_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             expected_duration: duration_estimate.mean,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             duration_buffer:  duration_estimate.std_dev * 1.2,  // ~90th percentile coverage
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             equipment:        equipment_needs.required_equipment,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             room_constraints: equipment_needs.room_requirements,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_constraints: get_patient_constraints(case.patient_id),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             priority:         case.urgency_level,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             turnover_class:   classify_turnover(case.cpt_code)  // clean, contaminated, sterile
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append enriched_case to enriched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store enriched cases for the solver to consume.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write enriched to database table "or-cases-today"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN enriched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Build the constraint model.** This step translates business rules into mathematical constraints the solver can process. The separation between business rules (which change frequently) and solver logic (which is stable) is intentional. When a new surgeon joins or a room gets renovated, you update the constraint configuration, not the solver code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_constraint_model(cases, rooms, staff_schedules):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = new ConstraintModel()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Decision variables: assign each case to a room and a start time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each case in cases:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case.room_var  = model.add_variable(domain = eligible_rooms(case))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case.start_var = model.add_variable(domain = [block_start_time ... block_end_time])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         case.end_var   = case.start_var + case.expected_duration + case.duration_buffer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Hard constraint: no overlap within a room (including turnover time).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each pair (case_a, case_b) where case_a != case_b:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF case_a.room_var == case_b.room_var:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 case_a.end_var + turnover_time(case_a, case_b) <= case_b.start_var
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 OR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 case_b.end_var + turnover_time(case_b, case_a) <= case_a.start_var
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Hard constraint: shared equipment cannot be double-booked.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each equipment_item in shared_equipment_list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cases_needing = filter cases where equipment_item in case.equipment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each pair in cases_needing:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.add_no_overlap_constraint(pair, setup_time = equipment_item.setup_minutes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Hard constraint: staff availability windows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each staff_member in staff_schedules:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         assigned_cases = filter cases covered by staff_member
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each case in assigned_cases:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.add_constraint(case.start_var >= staff_member.available_from)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.add_constraint(case.end_var <= staff_member.available_until)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Hard constraint: room capability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each case in cases:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_constraint(case.room_var in case.room_constraints)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Soft constraint: minimize total overtime (penalized in objective).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each room in rooms:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         room_end = max(case.end_var for cases assigned to room)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         overtime = max(0, room_end - room.block_end_time)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_to_objective(overtime * OVERTIME_PENALTY_WEIGHT)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Soft constraint: surgeon sequence preferences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each surgeon_preference in surgeon_preferences:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // e.g., "complex case first" = penalize if complex case isn't position 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model.add_soft_penalty(surgeon_preference.violation_cost)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Objective: minimize weighted sum of overtime + idle gaps + preference violations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model.set_objective(MINIMIZE)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Solve.** Hand the model to the solver engine. For batch mode, allow several minutes of compute time to find a high-quality solution. For replan mode, fix already-completed cases and give the solver a tight time limit (10-30 seconds).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION solve_schedule(model, mode):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF mode == "batch":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Overnight planning: take time to find optimal solution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         solver = create_solver(type = "CP-SAT")  // or MIP solver for smaller instances
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         solver.set_time_limit(300 seconds)        // 5 minutes max
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         solver.set_optimality_gap(0.02)           // stop if within 2% of proven optimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF mode == "replan":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Intraday: need a good answer fast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         solver = create_solver(type = "CP-SAT")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         solver.set_time_limit(30 seconds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Warm-start: fix cases that have already started or completed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each case where case.status in ["in_progress", "completed"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.fix_variable(case.room_var, case.actual_room)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model.fix_variable(case.start_var, case.actual_start_time)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = solver.solve(model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF result.status == "OPTIMAL" or result.status == "FEASIBLE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         schedule = extract_schedule(result)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         write schedule to database table "or-schedule-current"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN schedule
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // No feasible solution found. Constraints are too tight.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Return the infeasibility report so humans can decide what to relax.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN { status: "INFEASIBLE", conflicts: result.conflict_analysis() }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Handle real-time events.** Throughout the day, events arrive: cases finish early or late, cancellations happen, urgent add-ons appear. The replan trigger evaluates whether the disruption is significant enough to warrant re-optimization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION handle_or_event(event):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_schedule = read from database "or-schedule-current"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF event.type == "case_completed":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Update actual end time. Check if downstream cases need adjustment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         actual_end = event.timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         expected_end = current_schedule[event.case_id].expected_end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deviation = actual_end - expected_end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF abs(deviation) > REPLAN_THRESHOLD_MINUTES:  // e.g., 15 minutes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             enqueue_replan(reason = "duration_deviation", deviation = deviation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF event.type == "case_cancelled":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // A cancelled case frees room time. Replan to fill the gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         enqueue_replan(reason = "cancellation", freed_minutes = case.expected_duration)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF event.type == "add_on_case":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // New case needs to be inserted into today's schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         enrich_case(event.case_data)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         enqueue_replan(reason = "add_on", urgency = event.case_data.priority)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION enqueue_replan(reason, **kwargs):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Send to SQS with deduplication to prevent replan storms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If multiple events arrive within 60 seconds, batch them into one replan.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     send to replan queue with deduplication_id = "replan-" + current_minute()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Publish and visualize.** The optimized schedule is exposed via API for the OR dashboard, EHR integration, and mobile notifications to surgical teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION publish_schedule(schedule):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to API-accessible format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each room in schedule.rooms:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         room_timeline = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             room_id:    room.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             room_name:  room.display_name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             cases: [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     case_id:     case.id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     procedure:   case.procedure_name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     surgeon:     case.surgeon_name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     start_time:  case.optimized_start,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     end_time:    case.optimized_end,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     status:      case.current_status,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     confidence:  case.schedule_confidence  // how likely this time holds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 FOR each case in room.sequence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         write room_timeline to API cache
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Notify affected staff of schedule changes (if this was a replan).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF schedule.is_replan:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         changed_cases = find cases where start_time or room changed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each case in changed_cases:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             notify surgical team (surgeon, anesthesia, nursing) of new time/room
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3 and Google OR-Tools, check out the [Python Example](chapter14.07-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
