[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Batch solve time (20 rooms, 60 cases) | 30-120 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Replan solve time | 5-30 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Utilization improvement vs. manual | 5-15 percentage points |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Overtime reduction | 20-40% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Schedule stability (cases not moved on replan) | 85-95% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Days with many urgent add-ons (the schedule is constantly disrupted). Cases with highly uncertain durations (complex revisions, trauma). Facilities where surgeon preferences are treated as hard constraints rather than soft (the problem becomes over-constrained). And the political dimension: a mathematically optimal schedule that moves a senior surgeon's preferred time slot will be rejected regardless of its optimality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The optimization itself is the easy part. Getting a solver to produce a good schedule from well-formulated constraints is a solved problem in operations research. The hard parts are everything around it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Duration prediction is where you live or die.** If your predicted durations are systematically wrong (and they will be, initially), the optimized schedule is fiction. Invest heavily in duration modeling before you invest in fancy solver techniques. A simple heuristic scheduler with accurate durations will outperform an optimal solver with bad duration estimates every time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Surgeon buy-in is non-negotiable.** Surgeons who feel the system is dictating their schedule will simply ignore it. The successful implementations I've seen treat surgeon preferences as near-hard constraints initially, then gradually demonstrate value by showing "your cases finished 30 minutes earlier because we sequenced them better." Start by optimizing within their preferences, not against them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The replan frequency tradeoff is real.** Replan too often and the schedule feels unstable (staff hate constant changes). Replan too rarely and you're running a suboptimal schedule all afternoon because of a morning disruption. Most teams settle on replanning only when deviation exceeds 15-20 minutes or when a cancellation/add-on occurs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Turnover time is where the real gains hide.** Most people focus on case duration optimization, but the 25-45 minutes between cases is where utilization is actually lost. Sequencing similar cases back-to-back (same equipment, same setup) can shave 5-10 minutes per turnover. Over a 6-case room day, that's 30-60 minutes of recovered time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that surprised me most: the constraint that causes the most infeasibility isn't equipment or rooms. It's anesthesia coverage. When one anesthesiologist covers multiple rooms, their availability window becomes the binding constraint on the entire schedule. Model this carefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-day horizon optimization.** Instead of optimizing one day at a time, optimize the entire week. Cases that can flex between days get assigned to the day where they improve overall utilization. This requires tighter integration with the surgical scheduling system and longer solve times, but the utilization gains compound.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stochastic duration modeling.** Replace point estimates with probability distributions. Use Monte Carlo simulation to evaluate schedule robustness: "this schedule has a 90% probability of finishing all rooms by 5 PM." Requires historical duration data per procedure-surgeon pair (at least 20-30 observations per combination for stable distribution fitting).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration with downstream resources.** Extend the model to include PACU bed availability, ICU bed reservations, and sterile processing capacity. A schedule that's optimal for the OR but overwhelms the PACU at 2 PM isn't actually optimal for the hospital. This makes the model significantly larger but captures real operational constraints that manual schedulers track intuitively.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.4 (Nurse Staffing Optimization):** The staff schedules that constrain OR sequencing are themselves an optimization output
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.5 (OR Block Scheduling):** Block allocation determines which services have access to which rooms; sequencing operates within those blocks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.6 (Patient Flow / Bed Assignment):** Downstream bed availability constrains OR throughput; these systems should communicate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.7 (Length of Stay Prediction):** Duration prediction techniques applicable to surgical case duration modeling
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.5 (Hospital Census Forecasting):** Census forecasts inform whether add-on cases can be accommodated
